WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.380 --> 00:00:18.560
Come on, tell me honestly, what terrible things do you say to yourself that no one knows. One said, oh, I'm fat and ugly and I'll never lose weight. One said that my house is always dirty, I'm a really terrible stay-at-home mother. One said my children deserve better than me.

00:00:18.660 --> 00:00:27.760
And when everyone finished telling me all that, they didn't know that I called each husband and asked him to send me a picture of them when they were little.

00:00:27.980 --> 00:00:31.980
And I take out that picture, a little girl five fat, this big picture.

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:35.780
And I say, ok, now say the same things to this little girl.

00:00:35.860 --> 00:00:37.500
And none could.

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:39.220
Each of them burst into tears.

00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:43.360
I say, I can't, I can't say such awful things to that sweet little girl.

00:00:43.940 --> 00:00:46.920
I say, and you say it every day, to that sweet little girl.

00:00:47.120 --> 00:01:10.520
When I put that video on the internet, a lot of people told me, I now have a picture of myself as a child, small, and I put it somewhere, so that I can see it every day. And we have to learn that. We must learn to be gentle with ourselves. When we were little, we would never say such words to anyone, not even to ourselves when we look at that picture.

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:22.360
How do you say elevator pitch in English, if you wanted to tell someone who Kristina Kuzmic is, how would you pronounce it?

00:01:22.470 --> 00:01:23.900
Now it is a little more difficult in Croatia.

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:34.260
I would say, an ordinary imperfect woman who has been through a lot and now wants to be for others what she needed when she was at the bottom.

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:47.840
So I use my creativity through videos, through books, through speeches at conferences, to simply add a little humor and hope and encourage people a little.

00:01:50.300 --> 00:02:03.720
When did you feel that you started using humor? Do you have the feeling that humor was somehow a defense against what was happening in your life in those moments?

00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:18.480
I have always used humor. I remember when I was 12 years old and I lived in Osijek and the war started. My mom and dad sent me to my grandparents so I wouldn't be in Osijek.

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:43.900
I get there too, they lived in Novi Sad, I get there, a day later my grandfather has a heart attack, I see him having a heart attack, I have to call an ambulance and all that happens, he ends up in the hospital, the next day I fall off my bike and cut my knee big.

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:48.780
all that, in 48 hours everything happened terribly.

00:02:49.600 --> 00:02:53.020
Grandma takes me to visit him in the hospital.

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:57.780
And I, with 12 gojins and so much stress, my friends are in the low tide, I don't know what's happening with them.

00:02:58.220 --> 00:02:59.200
I write a song.

00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:02.320
My leg hurts, and my grandmother hurts.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:04.880
He's taking me to the hospital to see my godchild.

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:10.600
Even then, I had to use humor somehow as therapy.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:13.040
And at that time I didn't even think about it.

00:03:13.220 --> 00:03:15.020
that it's some kind of therapy for me.

00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:16.740
But that's...

00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:22.100
I have such memories from my childhood, where humor was really always a kind of medicine for me.

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:35.100
Would you say today, when you are probably much more mature than when you were 12 years old, that humor is therapy or an escape from problems?

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:39.420
Do you mask it or actually process it through humor?

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:43.760
I think it can be both, but for me it is medicine.

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:49.180
Because it's not that I'm now ignoring my problems, ignoring my feelings and just joking about everything.

00:03:50.379 --> 00:03:54.280
Especially people who already watch my videos or read my books know.

00:03:55.659 --> 00:04:01.120
I actually enjoy both that, and the processing, and really feeling everything.

00:04:02.840 --> 00:04:08.940
So, yes, humor can be a bad thing, if you just kind of ignore the important things.

00:04:09.070 --> 00:04:10.680
But I need these two.

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:16.480
In the first book, I wrote how, for me, going through life without humor is like eating soup with a fork.

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:23.580
It will be ok, but you will miss so much, because humor really helps us.

00:04:25.340 --> 00:04:27.020
Do you think laughter is healing?

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:28.780
Yes, it is for me, at least.

00:04:29.270 --> 00:04:32.060
But not only me, I see it in my followers.

00:04:32.860 --> 00:04:41.220
When I make a video about difficult things and then somehow add humor, Our body needs that.

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:48.520
Our body simply needs to laugh, to breathe a little from all that.

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:50.080
Let's relax a bit.

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:52.900
The world is too serious anyway.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:56.560
Yes, we have to. I always tell my children find the funny.

00:04:56.860 --> 00:04:58.000
You have to find the funny.

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:11.960
Do you think that, I mean, that's one of my challenges, you know, the topics I deal with here are quite difficult at times. Well, even mom knows. Well, son, come on, throw in some humor.

00:05:11.970 --> 00:05:14.180
Well, you see how that lady was a vida de marine for you.

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:17.140
Maybe you, Damir, were looking at the sight of de marine.

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:24.880
As she is 80 and something years old, she is cheerful, optimistic, witty and relaxed. Come on, be more like a vida de marine.

00:05:25.370 --> 00:05:26.720
I say, well, how can I do it when I don't know?

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:30.260
Can it be learned or...

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:34.260
Is this combination of serious and humorous actually possible?

00:05:35.580 --> 00:05:37.180
Possible, I think, is important.

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:46.800
I often say that it's mine. I don't see myself as a brand, but when Iko asks me what it's like, who is your brand?

00:05:47.360 --> 00:05:48.800
I always say hope and humor.

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:58.460
Hope and humor. I think it actually goes very well together. Because we are people who will feel all kinds of emotions.

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:19.580
And yes, we need vulnerable conversations, we need hope, we need to be honest, we need to talk openly about things that are uncomfortable and difficult, but at the same time you have to laugh, you have to find something funny in this strange life we live.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:21.200
Really weird, isn't it?

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:22.420
Very strange.

00:06:24.540 --> 00:06:26.300
Mine is very strange.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:29.140
Did you expect to be doing what you are doing today?

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:29.800
At all.

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:37.880
I'm really, in a way, living a dream that I never even dreamed of.

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:48.620
Because when I was little, there were no social networks. I never thought I would write a book. When I moved to America, they made fun of me for how terrible my English was.

00:06:49.460 --> 00:06:51.640
And then she wrote the books in English.

00:06:53.720 --> 00:07:09.440
And especially that, I don't know how much we will talk about my story, but when I broke up as a very young woman with two small children, I hated myself so much and thought that I had nothing good to offer not only to the world, but even to my children.

00:07:09.920 --> 00:07:21.860
So now, when I see that people not only watch my videos, but also write a comment that I helped them in some way, it's mind-blowing, as they say in Croatian.

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:23.480
Explode moz.

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:24.640
Just like that.

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:28.880
Maybe there are some better translations, but this is the literary translation.

00:07:29.120 --> 00:07:29.620
Yes, yes.

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:34.440
Can you relate to that emotion?

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:40.700
when someone writes you a comment on YouTube, you really helped me, you gave me hope, you made me laugh.

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:42.100
Do you relate to that?

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:44.360
Yes, I think so.

00:07:44.520 --> 00:07:46.080
Or maybe you feel like that today.

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:48.520
I, for one, have a problem connecting with it.

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:50.140
How do I mean connect?

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:52.920
You know when someone says thank you, you changed my life.

00:07:54.660 --> 00:07:58.920
Is it for bragging or is it some kind of different feeling?

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:02.660
My first thought comes to me when he says something like that.

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:04.280
Bogotovo, you mentioned my life.

00:08:04.460 --> 00:08:07.600
I always think, oh, don't give me any credit for that.

00:08:08.150 --> 00:08:19.860
Because maybe something I said gave you a little hope, but if your life really changed, you really had to work hard on it.

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:21.340
Give yourself credit for that.

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:27.360
So I don't look at myself like, ah, I'm so wonderful, I'm changing people's lives.

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:31.280
I just think, oh, I'm so grateful that it helped someone a little.

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:34.680
Because a lot of people helped me too.

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:38.680
Maybe something like a spark that will encourage, maybe change.

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:39.460
Yes, yes.

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:51.120
How was that period of moving to America and those first years there, all the way to that first marriage?

00:08:51.620 --> 00:09:15.240
That. I was a teenager and like all teenagers I was insecure. I was always a little different, strange, as you noticed from my wonderful song that I described when I was 12,

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:57.920
and then to move at that time to a completely new culture, I have no friends there, not only that, but my friends are in Osijek and Ratje, and I felt such guilt, like how am I allowed to enjoy everything there, everything is nice, and I moved with my parents, yes, my dad got the opportunity to be a professor at all the universities there. They always told us, we go until we things calm down in Croatia and then we return. And so it was difficult for me, I had no friends, they made fun of me at school, I was a weird immigrant to them.

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:14.060
And then I decided, I always liked to act and then I decided to join that drama group in high school and I finally found friends there because everyone is strange there and then it was a little easier for me.

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:35.900
And now I think that all these experiences actually somehow gave me, helped me to have empathy for teenagers, for people who were given something by life that maybe they didn't plan for. And then my parents were with me, when they decided to come back, I was already at college.

00:10:36.360 --> 00:10:37.900
So the parents are back.

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:52.560
Yes, everyone is now in Zagreb and I was at university, I had a good time and then I graduated straight from university, I think, and three weeks later I got married.

00:10:53.660 --> 00:10:56.680
I don't recommend getting married so young.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:58.840
Children, if you listen, listen.

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:07.500
I got married and then in the first year of marriage I realized this was not good.

00:11:07.740 --> 00:11:12.060
This marriage is really not healthy and I need to...

00:11:12.450 --> 00:11:13.080
I need to leave.

00:11:14.060 --> 00:11:14.780
I have to go.

00:11:14.780 --> 00:11:15.280
That.

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:22.120
And maybe a week later, just when I decided ok, that's it.

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:24.320
I find out I'm pregnant.

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:27.980
And I think, oh, oh, no way.

00:11:28.040 --> 00:11:29.000
Is it the first child or the second?

00:11:29.020 --> 00:11:29.720
First, first.

00:11:31.220 --> 00:11:35.500
I also think, there is no chance that my child will grow up in a divorced home.

00:11:36.360 --> 00:11:36.880
No chance.

00:11:37.759 --> 00:11:40.700
Somehow we will fix it, everything will be wonderful, everything will be fine.

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:51.660
And then I had a son and somehow my life became completely like a child's, I didn't even think about how unhealthy a marriage actually is.

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:57.820
And then very quickly, he was, I think, 90 months old when I got pregnant with my daughter.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:06.960
And then, when my daughter was a year and a half old, some things finally happened that I don't talk about publicly because of my children.

00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:12.020
Where I decided I must now leave.

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:14.520
I heard one, how do you say quote?

00:12:15.380 --> 00:12:15.880
Quote.

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:19.660
That. Someone said, I'm ringing in English now.

00:12:19.980 --> 00:12:25.260
It is better for children to come from a broken home than to live in a broken home.

00:12:25.680 --> 00:12:30.080
It is better for children to come from a broken home than to be kept in a broken one.

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:35.600
That. And when I read it, everything was clear to me. I suddenly knew.

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:39.620
Because I was afraid I would destroy the children if I divorced.

00:12:40.800 --> 00:12:45.380
And then I realized no, no, no, no, actually it will be better for them too.

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:53.799
And today, let's say with this maturity that you have right now, do you see some way how it could have worked or...

00:12:55.570 --> 00:13:07.160
Do you see what people actually often... It's hard to find a balance sometimes, like how much is my responsibility.

00:13:07.190 --> 00:13:10.680
I try to think in a way that everything is my responsibility.

00:13:10.690 --> 00:13:11.190
That.

00:13:11.310 --> 00:13:14.900
Ok, you've made the decision that you want to step on that man, but like that?

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:15.660
That.

00:13:16.100 --> 00:14:17.400
what I like about my first marriage, I really tried, we went to therapy together and I didn't go until I really felt it, I tried everything and now when I look at it and how hard it was and especially after I broke up it was a horror, I'm not a body to ask for money, I'm not a body for anything, I'm one body away and no drama I'm not a body So I ended up very poor I couldn't save up for me and the children I shared a small room with them I had a roommate in another I slept on the floor in my room until my friend gave me a mattress. I think it was very difficult for me, but not only financially, but I felt like a failure. Like I made a stupid decision. But I don't even regret that decision. Because now I have these wonderful children. But they deserve a better mother than me. When I broke up on the 27th of Linka.

00:14:17.960 --> 00:14:18.800
With two small children.

00:14:19.050 --> 00:14:34.000
That. And this was so hard for me and I really hated myself. I had no confidence whatsoever. Now I look at that 27-year-old Kristina and I'm so proud of her, I could cry.

00:14:34.580 --> 00:14:36.460
What a difficult decision it was.

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:50.080
And that I decided that and then, even though it was so hard, every day I got up and did everything I could for those children to make it nice for them, even though it was hard for us.

00:14:51.160 --> 00:15:05.080
It's such an interesting perspective now, like 20 shits later, how I look at those days completely differently. I can still see that they were very difficult, but I am so proud of myself.

00:15:05.600 --> 00:15:12.160
And now, especially since I'm in my second marriage, I actually see even more how unhealthy the first one was.

00:15:12.900 --> 00:15:15.660
Because now I have something that is the complete opposite.

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:19.860
And the eyes too, I wasn't perfect, of course, a woman in my first marriage.

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:23.520
It's not that I was all wonderful and he was a horror.

00:15:23.920 --> 00:15:30.180
Of course, we all make mistakes, we are not always the best.

00:15:32.680 --> 00:15:34.940
But yes, I think I made a good decision.

00:15:34.990 --> 00:16:05.280
And even, now I'm skipping a bit, but I want to say, my oldest son, We'll talk about him a little later. When he was going through difficult days, we were some kind of psychotherapist together, me and him. The psychotherapist also asks him, do you think that the divorce of your parents, how did it affect you negatively? Did that maybe somehow lead to that depression and what you're feeling now?

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:21.000
And he thought for a while and said, no, because if they hadn't split up, I wouldn't have Filip. Filip is my husband now. Because my husband is such a support to him. I immediately started crying too.

00:16:21.420 --> 00:16:30.980
Because I still, even though I knew I made a good decision, I think every parent still feels some guilt when they make that decision.

00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:41.520
Like, no one wants children to grow up in a divorced home. And I always felt a little guilty, even though I still knew that I had made a good decision.

00:16:41.980 --> 00:16:46.460
And when I heard that from my son, it somehow healed so much of me.

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:49.180
Yes, maybe you felt some guilty conscience.

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:50.240
That.

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:55.240
that this was the cause of his problems later.

00:16:55.490 --> 00:16:55.990
That.

00:16:56.360 --> 00:16:57.900
Well, that took Teresa's heart out of you.

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:08.900
And my daughter says the same thing, she is so grateful, they even went a couple of times, they are the ones now, a couple of times they are the order, we can't imagine you and dad together.

00:17:09.140 --> 00:17:10.319
What would that even look like?

00:17:10.720 --> 00:17:12.560
It doesn't make any sense to them.

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:17.439
And they respect and really love my brother so much.

00:17:17.699 --> 00:17:20.360
How many people stay in such marriages for the rest of their lives?

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:23.220
It is somehow especially here in the Balkans, still a little.

00:17:24.740 --> 00:17:26.600
Especially in the older generations, it is ingrained.

00:17:27.720 --> 00:17:30.160
An opinion is like staring until death.

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:40.420
Yes, and to tell you the truth, there were people, I won't say which people, who were very, very angry with me when I stayed.

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:42.700
Like, how can you do something like that?

00:17:42.880 --> 00:17:45.880
How can you do that to children?

00:17:45.960 --> 00:19:30.020
But what's interesting, when I look at the marriages of those people, those marriages are really unhappy and somehow it seems to me that people who are, who feel that they have to stay in an unhappy marriage, when someone else has the courage to leave it, it's like how you condemn yourself when I had to stay in an unhappy one. What do you think we should hear the story of your ex-husband now, that now he wrote a book and that he was going like this, that he was doing a tour, what would you hear what his side of the story was, I'm not sure now that you see each other, we assume that you are in some kind of contact that because I made the decision and it was also really difficult, they hated each other so much when I was me, he was the person that I left him, I was the person that this act did not try in therapy to at least try to fix something and then I decided that was sometime after a couple of months I moved into my small apartment with a roommate, and that's all because I don't want my children every time, because they would be with him almost every weekend, when he comes to pick them up so that they can see someone, I don't know, we didn't even talk once, you could feel it, that tension, and I didn't want that for my children, and then I called him and said Listen, come to dinner and we'll be together with the children. You and they don't have to talk at all. We can only talk about children. And if they have us together, if they feel that it's ok, if we don't hate each other, he has no chance.

00:19:31.060 --> 00:19:46.220
I think that around the seventeenth time when I called him, he finally said yes. And he came. And then it went slowly, I always invited him to everything, I don't know if you celebrate Father's Day there.

00:19:47.350 --> 00:19:50.120
Yes, at night, yes. It's not very popular.

00:19:50.760 --> 00:19:51.980
I mean, it should be.

00:19:52.090 --> 00:19:54.140
Women's Day and Mother's Day are popular somehow.

00:19:54.420 --> 00:20:00.420
Let's change that. Father's Day should be just as important. Mostly for Father's Day I would make a picnic for them.

00:20:01.300 --> 00:21:00.460
and I would say to the children ok, now dad will pick him up and you take him out on a picnic and things like that, I wasn't in love with him, I didn't want to win him back, but simply for the children to see that even though we are separated, that there doesn't have to be hatred and that was it for a long time until somehow he softened a little and now he still comes, they are now grown up but let's say my daughter just had her 20th birthday, I immediately called him and said it was on Saturday, come and when I started with a new one, I told him listen, I'll tell you right now my ex is always welcome in my home because of the children and if you're not ok with that I completely understand but I'm not the woman you should be and he's just as wonderful before him because of the children.

00:21:01.280 --> 00:21:03.580
So, to answer you, that is the question now.

00:21:04.780 --> 00:21:10.980
I think that at that time she was writing a book, it must have been that, I have no idea why she left me.

00:21:12.220 --> 00:21:13.360
That would be the title of the book.

00:21:13.660 --> 00:21:14.380
I have no idea.

00:21:15.050 --> 00:21:15.840
That would be called a book.

00:21:16.670 --> 00:21:21.760
And now, now I think maybe...

00:21:23.440 --> 00:21:25.940
Oh, I have no idea. I have no idea now, you see.

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:26.820
I have no idea.

00:21:30.100 --> 00:21:34.660
I think he understands and knows more than he might admit.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:37.720
I don't know if there is.

00:21:38.140 --> 00:21:43.380
He is not as open as I am to admit his problems.

00:21:44.780 --> 00:21:47.320
And why are you so open to admit your problems?

00:21:47.620 --> 00:21:48.900
You mean, is it for this one?

00:21:49.550 --> 00:21:50.900
That you can help someone?

00:21:51.330 --> 00:21:53.000
Is this also some kind of part of therapy?

00:21:53.160 --> 00:21:54.520
Maybe treatment?

00:21:55.540 --> 00:22:36.200
Because even as a child, whenever I pretended that everything was ok when it wasn't or I pretended that I didn't know, I was somehow a fake, it was such a terrible feeling, I just couldn't do it, I was terrified, I don't know if I'm the kind of person born that I don't like being fake, and I also think that a lot of people who don't share their problems or their insecurities, think that I have to be as perfect as possible in order to be loved.

00:22:37.620 --> 00:22:47.300
And I actually believe the opposite. I think that people need and want and love people who are real people, not fakes.

00:22:48.550 --> 00:22:51.880
I had a very strange insight for you the other day.

00:22:52.140 --> 00:22:53.420
Can I share it with you?

00:22:53.420 --> 00:22:53.940
Yes, please.

00:22:54.660 --> 00:23:04.280
You know how in our Western culture, Christianity is dominant and influential in societies.

00:23:05.720 --> 00:23:11.360
And actually one of the most extreme symbols we have seen in our lives is Jesus on the cross.

00:23:13.100 --> 00:23:18.560
I think that I have come to some conclusion as to why this is so and why this symbol exists.

00:23:18.940 --> 00:23:23.100
Now it has nothing to do with theology, with religion.

00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:24.960
Just my interpretation.

00:23:25.960 --> 00:23:28.040
And somehow it builds on what she just told you.

00:23:28.820 --> 00:23:38.200
I realized that, for example, people who are depressed and who are defending themselves from the outside world are somehow huddled together as if they are protecting themselves.

