I mean, I can't believe that I decided to do this, that I'm going to write this book now. And I talk to my psychotherapist and say, I don't know how, but I will try to, like, that contract.

00:47:46.900 --> 00:47:50.220
You interrupt. Yes, stop, stop, I can't, I can't write this.

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:55.600
And I say he to me, so Kristina, you are writing a love story.

00:47:56.480 --> 00:48:01.120
I still can't say it without getting sick. You are writing a love story between a mother and a son.

00:48:02.060 --> 00:48:05.600
And it completely changed my perspective.

00:48:06.460 --> 00:48:32.820
And then I'm sitting there paying, paying again, and I think, yes, even through the hardest days, actually especially through those hardest days, it was a love story. And now I'm thinking about any problem, maybe it's not that, maybe something much smaller with my little son, when I'm having a hard time, when I have that difficult day as a parent.

00:48:33.380 --> 00:48:36.460
I mean, I'm living a love story now.

00:48:38.300 --> 00:48:38.800
That.

00:48:40.860 --> 00:48:47.440
How do you find strength in those most difficult moments?

00:48:48.540 --> 00:49:02.720
After the divorce, she is alone with two children, a single mother, no money, her son is depressed, he has problems with addiction. How do you find strength in those moments anyway?

00:49:03.600 --> 00:49:10.020
I think it depends on how we define strength. Sometimes strength to me looks like staying in bed a little too long.

00:49:10.360 --> 00:49:16.540
Sometimes the strength seems to be crying for three hours alone in the toilet in the basement where no one can see me.

00:49:18.320 --> 00:49:23.880
Sometimes strength means simply doing something for yourself and not feeling selfish.

00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:32.140
But I don't know, I don't know how to give up.

00:49:33.380 --> 00:49:34.240
You just have to.

00:49:36.200 --> 00:49:42.980
I had to accept that this is not some time, slowly everything will get better.

00:49:43.620 --> 00:49:47.700
I knew that if it was better one day, it would be worse the next day maybe.

00:49:48.020 --> 00:49:59.240
And that's ok. Simply accepting to take each day one by one and often during that time I even thought, ok, hour by hour, maybe even minute by minute.

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:01.260
How will we survive this minute?

00:50:02.060 --> 00:50:03.100
How will we survive this hour?

00:50:03.100 --> 00:50:08.220
I can't even worry about tomorrow, but what can I do now?

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:19.220
And accept the same, don't let what is out of my control completely control me.

00:50:20.540 --> 00:51:20.840
And to simply say ok what can I do now there is always something I can do now maybe it's just to write my son some nice message maybe I'll go for a walk to leave the house where everything is tense but step by step I had no other choice step by step this was very important to me when you said I don't know how to give up I don't know if it's the first time you've said it now and you've come to your senses or maybe now for the first time maybe now for the first time out loud I don't know how to give up I think when something is so important I can't imagine what's more important to me than my children, then it's impossible to give up, that's the love story, you don't give up. And that was the most important thing for me when my son was having a hard time.

00:51:21.860 --> 00:51:23.900
I saw how much he hated himself.

00:51:23.900 --> 00:51:25.520
I saw how difficult it was for him.

00:51:26.300 --> 00:51:38.180
And I wanted him to know that even there and in those moments, even when you're on drugs and angry and what other people would see as a horrible person.

00:51:39.160 --> 00:51:44.300
Even then, you are so loved, I love you so much, you deserve love so much.

00:51:44.620 --> 00:51:52.400
I think that sometimes when we feel the worst, we deserve love, that we don't deserve mercy or forgiveness.

00:51:54.340 --> 00:52:00.000
It seems to me that this kind of behavior is a symptom of a huge search for love.

00:52:01.220 --> 00:52:31.640
That. Often when he was angry with me, when he had that rage during depression, He went to me the most. Later he told me, mom, because I knew you wouldn't leave me. I had to do something with that and I knew that you are firm and that you won't want me, that you love me so much that you won't leave me. So, some very screwed up compliment.

00:52:33.420 --> 00:52:50.380
But hey, at that time I thought, wow, he hates me and then later I found out, no, no, no, he hates himself. He hates himself. And I have to prove to him that he has no reason to hate himself.

00:52:51.240 --> 00:53:07.060
If I know who he is. Even when he acts like that. I know his heart. I know he has a good heart. I know that he is suffering, that it is difficult for him, and I am not saying that the way he behaves is okay. Of course it's not ok. But I know who you are. I know who you are and I love you.

00:53:10.360 --> 00:53:12.180
I guess now is a quieter period for some.

00:53:12.660 --> 00:53:13.840
Oh, now it's wonderful.

00:53:14.660 --> 00:53:15.680
Is. Yes, now...

00:53:15.720 --> 00:53:20.160
How many years have passed since those events and the most difficult period, let's say?

00:53:20.620 --> 00:53:33.560
He said that he started feeling depressed around 12, I didn't notice anything until about 13, then I thought, then I assumed, I thought too much, and that's a teenager, a typical teenager.

00:53:34.240 --> 00:53:49.040
And then he was 14 years old when I simply asked him, I didn't even plan to ask, somehow it came out to me, have you ever had the thought of taking your own life? And thank God he was honest with me and said yes.

00:53:51.520 --> 00:53:55.360
that, the whole world changes when you hear something like that as a parent.

00:53:55.990 --> 00:54:01.300
And from then until about 3-4 years, it was very, very, very difficult.

00:54:01.520 --> 00:54:02.380
Very difficult.

00:54:02.950 --> 00:54:08.080
And at that time I had to call the police, I was in the hospital, it was really difficult.

00:54:09.320 --> 00:54:15.460
And then around 17 it was as up and down, up and down as mental health goes.

00:54:16.440 --> 00:54:20.720
But now for the last two years it's really good.

00:54:20.880 --> 00:54:27.080
At that time when it was the worst, if someone had told me that we would be this close now.

00:54:28.310 --> 00:54:30.260
That he would be so good to me.

00:54:32.020 --> 00:54:33.660
Now I'm in Croatia, in America.

00:54:34.220 --> 00:54:35.940
Every couple of days he sends me a message.

00:54:36.240 --> 00:54:37.940
I am so thankful for you, Mom.

00:54:39.060 --> 00:54:40.880
Do you know how much you know me?

00:54:41.640 --> 00:54:43.540
I'm waiting for him to ask me for money or something.

00:54:43.660 --> 00:54:44.380
Why are you writing this to me?

00:54:44.710 --> 00:54:45.900
No, he just wants to tell me.

00:54:45.900 --> 00:54:46.960
They are so close to us.

00:54:48.340 --> 00:54:49.520
I couldn't imagine it for them.

00:54:49.840 --> 00:55:07.900
And me because of that PTSD, the cheese that says, when things were better and he would come towards me, let's say I'm cooking in the kitchen and he comes towards me and I immediately, all that, I'm tense, I think, now he'll shout, now he'll do something, and he'll come and hug me.

00:55:08.700 --> 00:55:25.140
And I had to do that, I had to attend a lot of psychotherapy courses, so that I could somehow learn to change what I expected from him and accept that it is real, that it is better.

00:55:26.240 --> 00:55:38.220
I still sometimes have anxiety when I see, for example, that he doesn't live at home anymore, but he sleeps over almost every day, he comes over for a night or two and if I see him, I think he sleeps too much.

00:55:38.910 --> 00:55:41.560
Or why doesn't she eat? Why does he eat so little?

00:55:41.620 --> 00:55:43.040
The anxiety immediately returned to me.

00:55:43.600 --> 00:55:48.920
And then I learned to say to that anxiety, I'll let you know if I need you.

00:55:50.020 --> 00:55:58.820
I don't need you now. I know you want to help me. I don't need you now. And that somehow helps me. Simply, somehow tell that anxiety.

00:55:59.320 --> 00:56:35.740
in fact, it was quite unfortunate that in that period when the child becomes a teenager, this same problem and such illness occurs, because you cannot generally distinguish whether these are normal teenage problems, flies, bugs in the head and so on, or is it some kind of more serious problem that how did you generally understand what helped you the most during that period? Of all the things you've tried, what would you say helped you the most?

00:56:36.590 --> 00:56:58.240
I noticed that he doesn't just separate from mom and dad, like a lot of teenagers. He separates himself from his friends. He separates himself from anything that used to bring him happiness. When I found out that he was taking drugs and drinking, it wasn't the same with his friends, going out, partying. He is alone in his room.

00:56:58.920 --> 00:57:07.860
drank the whole bottle of wine as fast as possible. I found a small bag with sugar because he would pour it into the bottle so that he could drink it as quickly as possible.

00:57:08.480 --> 00:57:12.620
I thought that was not normal teenage behavior.

00:57:13.740 --> 00:57:20.000
And let's say, I don't know, in the seventh, eighth grade they have all fives.

00:57:21.140 --> 00:57:22.100
Suddenly falling.

00:57:23.280 --> 00:57:25.620
I mean, that's the huge difference.

00:57:27.300 --> 00:57:45.840
So I knew something was wrong, and he didn't even know how to describe it. I think, many times people, parents ask, what is it? What happened? And teenagers, even us adults, sometimes don't know how to describe when we're having a hard time, we don't know what's happening in our body.

00:57:46.420 --> 00:58:07.720
He didn't know and then he would say, I don't know, leave it alone. From the beginning, I saw it as, before I knew that I was on drugs, before I threatened all that, I looked at him somehow, which is just general to say now, but I'll be honest, like a naughty child.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:25.240
I really believe that the children that people call naughty, almost 100%, are not naughty, but suffer. Suffer. There is a reason why they act like that.

00:58:26.280 --> 00:58:34.380
our job as a parent and to somehow find out that reason, to somehow really focus on the root of the problem.

00:58:34.880 --> 00:58:41.020
Because when he behaved like that and shouted at me and this and that, I would punish him. That didn't help.

00:58:41.240 --> 00:58:43.280
Because you cannot punish the press.

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:52.080
I remember at that time, people would tell me, well, you just have to be stricter with him. You have to, don't let him do this, don't do this and take his phone.

00:58:53.400 --> 00:58:55.540
And I tried, I tried all kinds of punishments.

00:58:56.020 --> 00:58:57.940
And that's it, everything got worse.

00:58:58.950 --> 00:59:02.060
You cannot punish depression or any mental illness.

00:59:02.170 --> 00:59:03.220
It cannot be punished.

00:59:05.880 --> 00:59:07.340
We tried everything too.

00:59:07.350 --> 00:59:08.840
He went to therapy.

00:59:08.880 --> 00:59:13.880
Then that psychotherapist said that he thinks it's more real.

00:59:13.880 --> 00:59:15.660
That maybe they should see a psychiatrist.

00:59:15.930 --> 00:59:19.180
He started taking the medicine.

00:59:19.290 --> 00:59:20.420
Those medicines did not help.

00:59:20.460 --> 00:59:21.900
Then we tried other drugs.

00:59:22.020 --> 00:59:24.000
I mean, that was...

00:59:24.020 --> 00:59:26.180
And it's always mentally a little bit very difficult.

00:59:26.180 --> 00:59:27.120
It's complicated.

00:59:27.500 --> 00:59:29.340
It's good that he wanted to take medicine at all.

00:59:29.350 --> 00:59:30.200
Well, at first it wasn't.

00:59:31.740 --> 00:59:34.540
But I think so much became desperate.

00:59:37.320 --> 00:59:42.340
And I am like a naive mother who wanted to encourage him.

00:59:42.340 --> 00:59:44.380
And she said, listen, that will help you.

00:59:44.710 --> 00:59:48.080
And when it didn't help right away, you know what helps right away?

00:59:48.280 --> 00:59:49.280
The drug helps immediately.

00:59:49.450 --> 00:59:50.600
Because then I don't feel anything.

00:59:50.980 --> 00:59:52.720
Then he actually started using drugs even more.

00:59:53.540 --> 00:59:55.320
I take this and immediately feel better.

00:59:55.570 --> 01:00:06.340
And I have to wait three months for this to start working at all, then it doesn't work, then I have various symptoms because of it and this, not symptoms, as they say, side effects.

01:00:07.380 --> 01:00:08.020
Follow up. That.

01:00:09.320 --> 01:00:16.460
I think he tried somewhere around 14 different medicines until we finally found something that helped.

01:00:16.870 --> 01:00:22.660
And I just want to say that if anyone listens to fight, don't give up.

01:00:23.480 --> 01:01:04.960
mental health is very complicated, but there is something that will help you, and what actually helped him the most, and that's why he actually decided to write the book with me, he started going to support groups, at first he didn't want to, and then like come on, you can be with teenagers for 3 hours, something is Monday for 3 hours, on Wednesday for 3 hours and then on Saturdays we went together as a family with other families and he met other teenagers there he sits there and those teenagers like that they talk openly about what he really feels, and he's never heard someone his age talk about it so openly.

01:01:05.560 --> 01:01:13.700
And for the first couple of weeks he was silent and suddenly he started talking to them openly.

01:01:14.040 --> 01:01:37.700
And he told me later, mom, I felt that I wasn't crazy, that it wasn't something abnormal with me, but simply, here, I have this mental illness, other people have it too, I see how they get better, after how much better, maybe I will get better too, it helped him so much, we have a whole chapter in the book about how much these groups helped him.

01:01:38.880 --> 01:02:06.520
And I think that, even if there are no such groups in Croatia, I think it proves that we have to talk about it openly, we have to. Because when you tell someone something that they feel, and they are ashamed of it or think it is not okay to say it out loud, and you hear it, that feeling and I do the same, it actually heals us so much, that we know we are not alone.

01:02:14.860 --> 01:02:16.060
What's going on in your head?

01:02:19.060 --> 01:02:20.880
Traba makes these uncomfortable silences a little difficult.

01:02:21.940 --> 01:02:24.260
So, are you the same with your son?

01:02:25.440 --> 01:02:26.820
She was silent and stood.

01:02:27.620 --> 01:02:28.140
And watched.

01:02:29.600 --> 01:02:33.760
Even in that one, more like, everyone is a little like that, everyone became a little uncomfortable.

01:02:33.880 --> 01:02:35.560
I kept quiet a little longer, didn't I?

01:02:36.900 --> 01:02:38.500
But to that my wife just like.

01:02:38.540 --> 01:02:41.040
why are you looking at me like that? I can't read your mind.

01:02:41.220 --> 01:02:44.100
I see that something is happening in your brain, that's why I asked.

01:02:45.120 --> 01:02:46.220
Something is happening.

01:02:46.700 --> 01:02:47.580
Maybe I'm hungry.

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:53.340
That.

01:02:54.300 --> 01:02:55.100
So, today is good.

01:02:55.790 --> 01:02:58.880
Is. And if you asked him, he would say just like that.

01:02:59.040 --> 01:03:00.640
He would say, I'm fine today.

01:03:01.330 --> 01:03:07.360
Because he always wants to be very honest with people, especially since we shared our story publicly.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:15.800
If mental illness isn't something you reach for, mental health is still wonderful.

01:03:15.910 --> 01:03:17.200
He still has hard days.

01:03:17.740 --> 01:03:20.960
A year ago, just last summer, it was very difficult for him.

01:03:21.440 --> 01:03:22.020
Very difficult.

01:03:22.230 --> 01:03:26.800
I'm all over, now my fear is back because I saw a big change in him.

01:03:27.340 --> 01:03:31.480
And then I found out that he stopped taking his medicine because he thought, well, I'm better.

01:03:32.520 --> 01:03:33.020
Now I can do without.

01:03:34.560 --> 01:03:35.520
And I can't do without it.

01:03:36.440 --> 01:03:41.340
And well, then he started five meds and now he's fine, but he still has rough days.

01:03:42.160 --> 01:03:48.040
And he is very honest with me. He calls me or comes to me and says today is a really hard day.

01:03:49.120 --> 01:04:01.740
But the difference is, after so many years of therapy and those support groups and drugs and doctors and all that, he knows what helps him and knows what he needs.

01:04:02.460 --> 01:04:06.440
And he often says, you know mom, depression lies to me.

01:04:07.680 --> 01:04:10.420
And I have to do the opposite of what my depression tells me.

01:04:10.800 --> 01:04:12.920
Depression tells me to stay in bed all day.

01:04:14.120 --> 01:04:21.360
Then when I notice that, oh, I want to stay in bed all day, that means I have to get up, the exact opposite I always do.

01:04:21.790 --> 01:04:26.100
When depression tells me, you're not hungry, you don't have to eat today.

01:04:26.900 --> 01:04:30.460
I have to eat something. When I want to isolate myself, no.

01:04:30.840 --> 01:04:32.700
I have to pick up the phone and call a friend.

01:04:33.100 --> 01:04:34.680
And make a plan with a friend.

01:04:35.200 --> 01:04:42.800
So, he simply understands, he says, when I'm having a hard day, then I know I have to do exactly the opposite of what I want.

01:04:44.860 --> 01:04:52.020
I assume that there are people who were depressed, were on medication, and later came off the medication and are still alive today.

01:04:53.040 --> 01:04:59.580
Without that, someone who may never have had such an experience, so maybe from the outside she would think for herself.

01:04:59.760 --> 01:05:02.720
I crossed paths with Aleksandar Stanković, well, you were with him as well.

01:05:04.840 --> 01:05:20.200
What if he thinks, ok, I just need to get my life in order, I need to have, spend time outside in nature, I need to be physically active, I need to have a good quality diet, a rich quality social life, be good to myself.

01:05:20.320 --> 01:05:26.400
You know, she's laying some healthy foundations and I won't need medicine.

01:05:26.640 --> 01:05:34.240
For example, when I spoke with Aleksandar, he told me that he satisfied everything and still could not do without medication.

01:05:35.340 --> 01:05:41.620
Because it's not just me thinking, it depends again, mentally it's always complicated.

01:05:42.300 --> 01:05:43.280
There are different types.

01:05:43.480 --> 01:05:47.360
There are places more situational.

01:05:48.440 --> 01:05:51.180
There are clinical places.

01:05:51.980 --> 01:06:08.640
My son believes, I have no idea, I'm not a doctor. He believes that somehow he will always struggle with it. Especially since he tried it without drugs. Well, he's still young now. Who knows, hormones are another thing, who knows how it will be when he is 30-40 years old.

01:06:09.520 --> 01:06:16.960
But I think it is important to know that there is no shame if you have to take it.

01:06:17.240 --> 01:06:18.800
Maybe you don't need a doctor in this life.

01:06:18.870 --> 01:06:24.980
That is also wonderful. But if you need it, take it as you would if you had diabetes, as you said.

01:06:25.400 --> 01:06:34.840
Yes, yes, yes. Or whatever, somehow people feel, if I take medicine, if I have to take medicine, then I am weak.

01:06:36.279 --> 01:06:39.400
We need to stop seeing it as mental health.

01:06:40.440 --> 01:06:43.640
Somehow you need something a little more than a walk and meditation.

01:06:45.100 --> 01:06:49.520
Yes, maybe people think that it is not natural as it is not part of nature.

01:06:49.520 --> 01:06:53.360
I want to live like any other healthy person.

01:06:54.100 --> 01:06:54.600
That.

01:06:55.460 --> 01:07:00.820
Naturally from the food that the earth gives me, the sun and so on.

01:07:02.600 --> 01:07:06.560
Then they may feel unhappy and frustrated that they can't.

01:07:07.460 --> 01:07:09.100
Why can Marko and I can't?

01:07:09.340 --> 01:07:18.240
That. But again, a disease is a disease. I don't know if they would feel that way about taking medication for something that is not a mental illness.

01:07:19.400 --> 01:07:32.660
I often think, the most important thing for me is to be able to achieve this, and I don't think I will be able to before I die, it would be the happiest, if we can completely get rid of that shame when it comes to mental illness.

01:07:33.360 --> 01:07:43.360
Because I often think, for example, when someone has a headache, they go to their mom, dad, wife, whoever, hey, do you have something, really, I have a headache.

01:07:43.620 --> 01:07:49.740
They immediately say, there's no shame, there's no shame, oh, I don't want anyone to know, my head hurts, and then he takes medicine and he's better.

01:07:51.200 --> 01:08:03.640
If only the body could tell you, if it looked at mental illness that way. And if a child or even an adult would go up to someone and say hey, I don't feel good.

01:08:03.680 --> 01:08:05.520
I don't know exactly what it is, but I don't feel well.

01:08:05.840 --> 01:08:06.480
I need something.

01:08:08.540 --> 01:08:11.420
How many people would actually still be there who are no longer there?

01:08:12.180 --> 01:08:17.080
That they simply felt that it was normal, that it was okay to ask for help.

01:08:18.040 --> 01:08:21.319
That there is nothing strange about them. That they are not abnormal.

01:08:21.740 --> 01:08:23.180
But here, I'm not okay.

01:08:23.359 --> 01:08:24.020
I need help.

01:08:25.440 --> 01:09:01.600
maybe it's a question of what, if we hit each other and I don't know now, some muscle hurts so we apply some kind of gel over it so that it hurts less, let's say with globes or something like that you say, maybe we have a sore throat, let's take some throat medicine for the throat, they are all somehow parts of our body or something, and maybe this is when we identify our psyche with what we really are. And then maybe people wonder why I take medicine to cure what I really am.

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:05.819
It's not my hand, it's me. This is still my hand, my...

01:09:06.319 --> 01:09:12.160
We tie our value to too many things that are beyond our control.

01:09:13.600 --> 01:09:22.080
My son wrote in the view he wrote why should I feel shame about mental illness when I didn't choose it.

01:09:22.880 --> 01:09:26.460
I can feel the shame I was towards my mother when it was the hardest for me.

01:09:27.120 --> 01:09:30.240
I can feel shame for stealing money to make friends.

01:09:30.480 --> 01:09:33.920
I feel ashamed and I apologized and that's all.

01:09:34.420 --> 01:09:39.859
Why should you feel shame for something that I did not choose and decide?

01:09:41.420 --> 01:09:49.980
And that's the problem. We attach our value to things that are not at all under our control. And that's not fair.

01:09:50.520 --> 01:09:53.000
And that's what parents do with their children when their children are suffering.

01:09:53.319 --> 01:10:03.600
For a while, I tied my worth to his problems, to his insecurities, whatever.

01:10:04.340 --> 01:10:06.020
My value was tied there.

01:10:06.360 --> 01:10:09.380
That's not fair. It's not fair to me, it's not fair to him.

01:10:10.400 --> 01:10:20.140
You made a great video where you described the attitude towards mental illnesses throughout the ages.

01:10:20.680 --> 01:10:21.180
That.

01:10:22.640 --> 01:10:27.100
What was at the beginning a few thousand years before Christ, the Middle Ages.

01:10:29.080 --> 01:10:31.160
It was quite interesting to see actually.

01:10:31.680 --> 01:10:40.740
And until a few years ago, and maybe a decade, it was a huge taboo topic.

01:10:41.480 --> 01:10:45.440
Maybe I could give a short story if you still remember the concept of how you are.

01:10:45.660 --> 01:10:53.700
Yes, I don't remember exactly what it was for each decade, but the one that started where I don't know what kind of raclava it was.

